    {
      "id": "57b24110a0ca7c64bb66845132f140960560424d",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 176,
        "name": "Liang Zhen",
        "email": "liang.zhen@intel.com",
        "username": "liangzhen",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2014-01-24 03:16:39.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\n(7 comments)\n\nsorry I still didn't see buffer overflow check in this patch, so the only fence is:\n cfs_vsnprintf()\n LASSERT(size > 0);\n \nThis is not good enough, because it's an assertion but we don't want to LBUG only because user passed in a small buffer, also, size_t is unsigned value which means negative value will be pass the assertion",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
    {
      "id": "7e69c41325fa0547f7255462d0e4738949506605",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 163,
        "name": "Gregoire Pichon",
        "email": "gregoire.pichon@eviden.com",
        "username": "pichong"
      },
      "date": "2014-01-24 13:15:27.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\nLiang,\n\nI am sorry but I don't understand your point.\n\nIn my opinion, the code is safe. Buffer overflow is not possible because:\n- cfs_snprinf(buffer, size, ...) write at most _size_ bytes (including the\n  trailing null byte) and returns the actual number of bytes (not including\n  the trailing null byte) written to _buffer_\n- all print subroutines called by cfs_print_nidlist() in the stack down to\n  cfs_snprintf() have the same semantic than cfs_snprintf()\n- calls are all made like this:\n     i += xxx_print(buffer + i, count - i, ...);\n     i being the offset in the buffer where next characters can be written\n\nIt means _i_ is always strictly less than _count_. There is no need to\nhave additional check 'i < count'.\n\nThe entry points cfs_expr_list_print() and cfs_print_nidlist(), which are\nexported symbols, have an additional check to ensure count parameter is\nstrictly positive.\n\nDuring the nidlist printing, once i equals count-1, cfs_snprintf() does\nnot write any additional character and returns 0. There is no buffer overflow.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
    {
      "id": "d80ec6e1ddd3347d1a35bc53bdae088eab6bb635",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 176,
        "name": "Liang Zhen",
        "email": "liang.zhen@intel.com",
        "username": "liangzhen",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2014-01-24 16:22:59.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5: Code-Review+1\n\nindeed, sorry for noise, thanks for explaining",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
